{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476326"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:44:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583751"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:27:40+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:27:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13729"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13729","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13729"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.07,0.01,0.02,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6348"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93109"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6348","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6348"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13729"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76462"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"1440"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"10773"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31970"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/93109"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 12-year-old boy presents to his General Practice clinic with his parents for a routine check-up. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His father was recently diagnosed with familial adenomatous polyposis at age 40 after a colonoscopy revealed hundreds of adenomatous polyps throughout his colon.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGenetic testing confirmed a pathogenic mutation in the APC gene.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely mode of inheritance of familial adenomatous polyposis in this family?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Autosomal recessive","X-linked recessive","Mitochondrial","Y-linked","Autosomal dominant"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EFamilial adenomatous polyposis is an \u003Cstrong\u003Eautosomal dominant\u003C/strong\u003E condition caused by a pathogenic mutation in the APC gene. Individuals with a mutation have a 50% chance of passing it on to each of their children, regardless of sex. The father\u2019s diagnosis at a young age and hundreds of polyps is highly suggestive of classic FAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFAP is not an \u003Cstrong\u003Eautosomal recessive\u003C/strong\u003E condition, as it can be passed on from one affected parent. Autosomal recessive conditions typically require both parents to be carriers.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFAP is not \u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked recessive\u003C/strong\u003E, as it affects both males and females equally. X-linked recessive conditions are typically more severe in males and rarely affect females.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial\u003C/strong\u003E conditions are maternally inherited, as mitochondria are passed on through the egg from the mother. FAP can be inherited from either the mother or father, so it is not mitochondrial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EY-linked\u003C/strong\u003E conditions are exceedingly rare and only affect males, as the Y chromosome is only present in males. FAP affects both sexes, so it cannot be Y-linked.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Familial adenomatous polyposis is an autosomal dominant condition caused by a mutation in the APC gene."],"references":["Chung DC, Rodgers LH. Clinical manifestations and diagnosis of familial adenomatous polyposis. In: UpToDate [online]. 2024. Available at: https://www.uptodate.com/contents/clinical-manifestations-and-diagnosis-of-familial-adenomatous-p...","Kyriakidis F, Kogias D, Venou TM, Karlafti E, Paramythiotis D. Updated Perspectives on the Diagnosis and Management of Familial Adenomatous Polyposis. Appl Clin Genet. 2023 Aug 14;16:139-153. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC10439286/","Talseth-Palmer BA. The genetic basis of colonic adenomatous polyposis syndromes. Hereditary Cancer in Clinical Practice. 2017;15(1):5. Available at: https://hccpjournal.biomedcentral.com/articles/10.1186/s13053-017-0065-x#citeas"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76462"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13729"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"76462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/76462"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-20T16:16:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-20T16:16:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6348"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"93109"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":